{"data":{"wordpressPost":{"title":"a11y: Tables and Borders","content":"<html><head></head><body><p>\t\t\t\tThe past few weeks at work I&#x2019;ve been working a lot with tables. I was testing for accessibility using <a href=\"http://www.apple.com/ca/accessibility/osx/voiceover/\">VoiceOver</a> when I ran into an interesting discovery.</p>\n<p><!--more--></p>\n<p>To preface, tables can be categorized into two types: <strong>layout</strong> tables and <strong>data</strong> tables. Layout tables are used to position elements around (not really a thing anymore, thank God). Data tables are for presenting tabular data. In VoiceOver, a data table with proper markup will appear under the &#x201C;Tables&#x201D; rotor menu, as shown in the screenshot below.</p>\n<p></p><div class=\" gatsby-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;overflow:hidden;max-width:100%\" data-reactroot><div style=\"width:100%;padding-bottom:91.69632265717674%\"></div><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center;opacity:1;transition-delay:500ms\"><picture><img sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\" srcset=\"/static/8226ea987184cd04278d2482cbd1336a/19bd1/table-voiceover.png 163w,\n/static/8226ea987184cd04278d2482cbd1336a/d3bcb/table-voiceover.png 325w,\n/static/8226ea987184cd04278d2482cbd1336a/dbb61/table-voiceover.png 650w,\n/static/8226ea987184cd04278d2482cbd1336a/b28c0/table-voiceover.png 843w\" src=\"/static/8226ea987184cd04278d2482cbd1336a/dbb61/table-voiceover.png\" alt style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center;opacity:1;transition:opacity 500ms\"></picture><noscript><picture><img sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\" srcset=\"/static/8226ea987184cd04278d2482cbd1336a/19bd1/table-voiceover.png 163w,\n/static/8226ea987184cd04278d2482cbd1336a/d3bcb/table-voiceover.png 325w,\n/static/8226ea987184cd04278d2482cbd1336a/dbb61/table-voiceover.png 650w,\n/static/8226ea987184cd04278d2482cbd1336a/b28c0/table-voiceover.png 843w\" src=\"/static/8226ea987184cd04278d2482cbd1336a/dbb61/table-voiceover.png\" alt=\"\" style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;opacity:1;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center\"/></picture></noscript></div><p></p>\n<p>To try this out, you can go to any page with a data table (such as <a href=\"http://s.codepen.io/tetchi/debug/bEwVBV\">this</a> one), and press <code>cmd + f5</code> to activate VoiceOver. Hit <code>ctrl + alt + u</code> to bring up the rotor, and use the left and right arrows to navigate to the Tables rotor menu.</p>\n<p>The table that I was working on did not have any table headers by design, which is a no-no according to <a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/tables/data#th\">WebAIM&#x2019;s guidelines</a>. For this reason I totally expected VoiceOver to view my tables as a layout table, and that it would not appear in the Tables rotor menu.</p>\n<p>To my surprise, the table <strong>did</strong> appear in the rotor menu! You can see for yourself in this <a href=\"http://s.codepen.io/tetchi/debug/BjLNwv\">CodePen</a> and in the gif below.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://s.codepen.io/tetchi/debug/bEwVBV\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"></a></p><div class=\" gatsby-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;overflow:hidden;max-width:100%\" data-reactroot><div style=\"width:100%;padding-bottom:64.76793248945148%\"></div><a href=\"http://s.codepen.io/tetchi/debug/bEwVBV\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center;opacity:1;transition-delay:500ms\"><picture><img sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\" srcset=\"/static/960ebeeff717f2e64cc72086f084bcb8/79246/table.gif 163w,\n/static/960ebeeff717f2e64cc72086f084bcb8/669a5/table.gif 325w,\n/static/960ebeeff717f2e64cc72086f084bcb8/b5c6a/table.gif 650w,\n/static/960ebeeff717f2e64cc72086f084bcb8/9abac/table.gif 948w\" src=\"/static/960ebeeff717f2e64cc72086f084bcb8/b5c6a/table.gif\" alt style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center;opacity:1;transition:opacity 500ms\"></picture><noscript><picture><img sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\" srcset=\"/static/960ebeeff717f2e64cc72086f084bcb8/79246/table.gif 163w,\n/static/960ebeeff717f2e64cc72086f084bcb8/669a5/table.gif 325w,\n/static/960ebeeff717f2e64cc72086f084bcb8/b5c6a/table.gif 650w,\n/static/960ebeeff717f2e64cc72086f084bcb8/9abac/table.gif 948w\" src=\"/static/960ebeeff717f2e64cc72086f084bcb8/b5c6a/table.gif\" alt=\"\" style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;opacity:1;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center\"/></picture></noscript></a></div><p></p>\n<p>I was a bit stumped, so I asked my coworker <a href=\"https://twitter.com/newtron\">Dave</a> for his thoughts. He suggested that maybe the border between the rows had something to do with it. So I went back to CodePen, removed the borders, and turned on VoiceOver. Lo and behold, the table no longer showed up in VoiceOver! CodePen demo <a href=\"http://s.codepen.io/tetchi/debug/BjLNwv\">here</a>.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://s.codepen.io/tetchi/debug/BjLNwv\"></a></p><div class=\" gatsby-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;overflow:hidden;max-width:100%\" data-reactroot><div style=\"width:100%;padding-bottom:64.76793248945148%\"></div><a href=\"http://s.codepen.io/tetchi/debug/BjLNwv\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center;opacity:1;transition-delay:500ms\"><picture><img sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\" srcset=\"/static/e63eca751fe7eb702fd84557eab00ebb/79246/table_no_border.gif 163w,\n/static/e63eca751fe7eb702fd84557eab00ebb/669a5/table_no_border.gif 325w,\n/static/e63eca751fe7eb702fd84557eab00ebb/b5c6a/table_no_border.gif 650w,\n/static/e63eca751fe7eb702fd84557eab00ebb/9abac/table_no_border.gif 948w\" src=\"/static/e63eca751fe7eb702fd84557eab00ebb/b5c6a/table_no_border.gif\" alt style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center;opacity:1;transition:opacity 500ms\"></picture><noscript><picture><img sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\" srcset=\"/static/e63eca751fe7eb702fd84557eab00ebb/79246/table_no_border.gif 163w,\n/static/e63eca751fe7eb702fd84557eab00ebb/669a5/table_no_border.gif 325w,\n/static/e63eca751fe7eb702fd84557eab00ebb/b5c6a/table_no_border.gif 650w,\n/static/e63eca751fe7eb702fd84557eab00ebb/9abac/table_no_border.gif 948w\" src=\"/static/e63eca751fe7eb702fd84557eab00ebb/b5c6a/table_no_border.gif\" alt=\"\" style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;opacity:1;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center\"/></picture></noscript></a></div><p></p>\n<h3>What about transparent borders?</h3>\n<p>Just for fun, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/kpeatt\">Kyle</a> wanted to see what would happen if you set the border&#x2019;s colour to <code>transparent</code>. Funny enough, tables with <code>transparent</code> borders are still picked up by VoiceOver as data tables.</p>\n<p></p><div class=\" gatsby-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;overflow:hidden;max-width:100%\" data-reactroot><div style=\"width:100%;padding-bottom:71.9298245614035%\"></div><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center;opacity:1;transition-delay:500ms\"><picture><img sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\" srcset=\"/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/19bd1/transparent_border.png 163w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/d3bcb/transparent_border.png 325w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/dbb61/transparent_border.png 650w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/6b691/transparent_border.png 975w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/91670/transparent_border.png 1300w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/dfd8d/transparent_border.png 1950w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/759b6/transparent_border.png 1995w\" src=\"/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/dbb61/transparent_border.png\" alt style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center;opacity:1;transition:opacity 500ms\"></picture><noscript><picture><img sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\" srcset=\"/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/19bd1/transparent_border.png 163w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/d3bcb/transparent_border.png 325w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/dbb61/transparent_border.png 650w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/6b691/transparent_border.png 975w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/91670/transparent_border.png 1300w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/dfd8d/transparent_border.png 1950w,\n/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/759b6/transparent_border.png 1995w\" src=\"/static/7b1e39d057289cd80913be4b365c9e6a/dbb61/transparent_border.png\" alt=\"\" style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;opacity:1;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center\"/></picture></noscript></div><p></p>\n<h3>TLDR</h3>\n<p>VoiceOver uses borders as a criteria to determine if a table is a data table or not. Thus you <em>could</em> have a data table without any headers, though that&#x2019;s not recommended.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>I&#x2019;ve only tested this in VoiceOver in Chrome and Safari, but I&#x2019;m curious to see if other screen readers such as JAWS behave in a similar fashion. Give me a shout or leave a comment if you know!</p>\n<p>Shoutouts to <a href=\"https://twitter.com/newtron\">Dave</a> for his help and insights on this topic!</p>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>UPDATE: 02/07/2015:</strong> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/handcoding\">@handcoding</a> on Twitter linked me to a couple of pages that explain how Chrome and Firefox determine if a table is a data table or a layout table. Well worth checking out, thanks Ashley!</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://code.google.com/p/chromium/codesearch#chromium/src/third_party/WebKit/Source/modules/accessibility/AXTable.cpp&amp;sq=package:chromium&amp;l=102&amp;dr=CSs&amp;rcl=1435549126\">Chrome heuristics</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://asurkov.blogspot.hu/2011/10/data-vs-layout-table.html\">Firefox heuristics</a></li>\n</ul>\n</body></html>","wordpress_id":4513},"allWordpressWpComments":{"edges":[{"node":{"content":"<p>Thanks for reading, Toby! 🙂</p>\n","author_name":"tetchi","date":"January 24th, 2017"}},{"node":{"content":"<p>I just discovered the issue with VoiceOver and border independently&#8230; I felt an obligation to post it somewhere and was glad to see that you beat me to it. Thanks for the info&#8230; and for the details regarding Chrome and Firefox!</p>\n","author_name":"Toby Rush","date":"January 17th, 2017"}}]}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"a11y-tables-and-borders","wordpressId":4513,"newerPostSlug":"time-stories-a-board-game-experience-like-no-other","olderPostSlug":"japan-trip-2015-part-5-okinawa"}}